<title>USA: DuPont Co benefits not for temp workers - WSJ.</title>
<headline>DuPont Co benefits not for temp workers - WSJ.</headline>
<dateline>NEW YORK 1997-01-16</dateline>
<text>
<p>DuPont Co did not have to pay standard employee benefits to a contract worker, according to a decision by a federal appeals court in Richmond, Va., that is expected to soothe corporate fears about paying such benefits, The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday.</p>
<p>The newspaper calls the decision, handed down late last week, the first appellate-court decision on the subject since a federal appeals court in San Fransisco ruled in October that Microsoft Corp had wrongly classified some workers as independent contractors and had to compensate them retroactively for benefits.</p>
<p>In the DuPont case, the Fourth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a lower court ruling that the company was not required to provide life insurance and other coverage because its benefits plan explicitly excluded contract workers, the story said.</p>
